title: Intelligence Analyst / Assistant Security Manager
description: Fulfilled the duties of the Intelligence Officer for the squadron in planning, coordinating, executing, and supporting squadron operations through analysis, production, collections, and disseminate to all sections and individuals who need information in order to complete respective missions or tasks. Served as the Assistant Security Manager ensuring the squadron complies with policies and regulations regarding physical and information security for classified material. Performed as squadron anti-terrorism force protection officer conduction threat vulnerability assessments and maintaining liaison with government and private agencies concerning local threats and coordinating anti-terrorism plans and security matters. Was the functional area manager for four areas (Intelligence Oversight, Information and Personnel Security Program, Anti-Terrorism and IR) and received a grade of Mission Capable with No Discrepancies on each program during the Commanding General’s Inspection. Reviewed and evaluated investigation, personnel files, and other records to recommend to the Security Manager to grant, deny, revoke, suspend, or restrict security clearance access consistent with national security and/or suitability issues in the Joint Personnel Adjudication System (JPAS). Solely responsible for command’s information and personnel security program to include but not limited to education, clearance processing, indoctrinating and debriefing, personnel file maintenance, access control, visit requests, classified safeguarding and storage, document control, and inspections. Created and updated security policy and ensured compliance of a 500 member organization. Trained, mentored, and supervised personnel in intelligence oversight and security procedures. Created a security badge system and implemented access control procedures. Ensured physical and information security compliance for two vaults, three secure rooms, and seven restricted access areas with no security violations.

title: Platoon Sergeant / Commander
description: Senior Enlisted Marine and Advisor for a platoon/staff of over 40 Marines. Advised the Platoon Commander on tactical employment of the platoon and relevant personnel issues. Managed the discipline, accountability, and welfare of the Marines in the platoon, and the logistical support and timely re-supply of the platoon during field, garrison, and combat operations. Developed and executed performance based training using the Infantry Training and Readiness Manual and other relevant publications. Ensured strict accountability, serviceability, and cleanliness of all weapons, ammunition, vehicles, communication gear, and personal protective equipment (PPE) issued to the platoon. Trained Marines in the platoon in all aspects of the use and escalation of force to include: justifications and circumstances for the use of deadly force; rules of engagement; room clearing techniques for close quarters fighting and MOUT; and immediate actions in response to nuclear, biological, and chemical (NBC) threats with the proper use of protective masks and gear. Trained and maintained current weapons qualifications and records for all Marines on an annual basis for the following weapons: M240B Medium Machinegun, M16A4 Rifle, M249 Squad Automatic Weapon (SAW), M9A1 Beretta 9mm pistol, M203 40mm grenade launcher, and the M67 Fragmentation Hand Grenade. Managed all of the platoons annual, semi-annual, and quarterly training requirements and records. Performed administrative functions of the platoon and ensure all data is updated and accurate while supervising the Section Leaders counseling program that were under my charge. Assumed all duties and responsibilities of the Platoon Commander during periods of incapacity and non-availability.

title: Platoon Sergeant / Commander
description: Senior Enlisted Marine and Advisor for a platoon/staff of over 40 Marines. Advised the Platoon Commander on tactical employment of the platoon and relevant personnel issues. Managed the discipline, accountability, and welfare of the Marines in the platoon, and the logistical support and timely re-supply of the platoon during field, garrison, and combat operations. Developed and executed performance based training using the Infantry Training and Readiness Manual and other relevant publications. Ensured strict accountability, serviceability, and cleanliness of all weapons, ammunition, vehicles, communication gear, and personal protective equipment (PPE) issued to the platoon. Trained Marines in the platoon in all aspects of the use and escalation of force to include: justifications and circumstances for the use of deadly force; rules of engagement; room clearing techniques for close quarters fighting and MOUT; and immediate actions in response to nuclear, biological, and chemical (NBC) threats with the proper use of protective masks and gear. Trained and maintained current weapons qualifications and records for all Marines on an annual basis for the following weapons: M240B Medium Machinegun, M16A4 Rifle, M249 Squad Automatic Weapon (SAW), M9A1 Beretta 9mm pistol, M203 40mm grenade launcher, and the M67 Fragmentation Hand Grenade. Managed all of the platoons annual, semi-annual, and quarterly training requirements and records. Performed administrative functions of the platoon and ensure all data is updated and accurate while supervising the Section Leaders counseling program that were under my charge. Assumed all duties and responsibilities of the Platoon Commander during periods of incapacity and non-availability.
name: Michael DeMark

title: Ground Sensor Operator
description: Operated, implanted and monitored unmanned ground sensors that detect enemy movement and activity to provide early warning for coalition forces as well as counter IED, High Value Target Identification, Force Protection, and border security. Experienced in both the testing and evaluation and operation of Tactical Remote Sensor Systems and Unmanned Ground Sensors. Employed numerous types of sensors including seismic, magnetic, infrared and thermal to provide indications and warning (I&W), targeting, information and queuing for intelligence collection. Prepared various types of remote sensor surveillance devices for air and hand emplacement methods in areas previously determined. Monitored and interpreted sensor devices by reading out audio and visual transmissions. Made recommendations to and assists the intelligence officer in selecting areas, routes, and specific sites to be employed. Provided timely, and accurate data concerning enemy location, direction, speed of movement, and strength. Assisted in testing and evaluating new sensor surveillance equipment and ancillary devices.

Performed as squadron anti-terrorism force protection officer conduction threat vulnerability assessments and maintaining liaison with government and private agencies concerning local threats and coordinating anti-terrorism plans and security matters. Was the functional area manager for four areas (Intelligence Oversight, Information and Personnel Security Program, Anti-Terrorism and IR) and received a grade of Mission Capable with No Discrepancies on each program during the Commanding General’s Inspection. Reviewed and evaluated investigation, personnel files, and other records to recommend to the Security Manager to grant, deny, revoke, suspend, or restrict security clearance access consistent with national security and/or suitability issues in the Joint Personnel Adjudication System (JPAS). Solely responsible for command’s information and personnel security program to include but not limited to education, clearance processing, indoctrinating and debriefing, personnel file maintenance, access control, visit requests, classified safeguarding and storage, document control, and inspections. Created and updated security policy and ensured compliance of a 500 member organization. Trained, mentored, and supervised personnel in intelligence oversight and security procedures. Created a security badge system and implemented access control procedures. Ensured physical and information security compliance for two vaults, three secure rooms, and seven restricted access areas with no security violations.
